Space-Time Prediction of Bike Share Demand - Indego in Philadelphia, PA

Zizhao He

8/7/2020

1. Executive Summary

A bike-share program is a service in which bicycles are made available for shared use to individuals on a short term basis for a price or free. It allows people to borrow a bike from a dock and return it at another dock belonging to the same system. The central concept of bike-share is to provide free or affordable access to bicycles for short-distance trips in an urban area as an alternative to motorised public transport or private vehicles, thereby reducing congestion, noise, and air pollution. Whats more, bicycle-sharing systems have also been cited as a way to solve the last mile problem and connect users to public transit networks. People use bike-share for various reasons. One of the most important reasons is that, some who would otherwise use their own bicycle have concerns about theft or vandalism, parking or storage, and maintenance, which would be avoided through participating in a local bike-share program.

The research object of this paper is the Indego bike-share system in Philadelphia which features hundreds of bikes available 24 hours per day, 7 days per week, and 365 days per year. The locations of existing stations were selected based on proximity to community resources, employment centers, bike infrastructure, and transit in consultation with partner agencies, institutions, community groups, and the public. Currently, the system features over 500 bikes and 60+ stations located across Philadelphia in Center City and parts of North, South, and West Philadelphia.

One of the biggest operational challenges of bike share systems like Indego is re-balancing - getting bikes to stations that are anticipated to have demand but lack bikes. Figuring out how to do this is one of the keys to operating a successful system. The algorithm model introduced in this paper aims to predict Indego bike share demand by taking time, physical and socio-economic factors into account, so that the model can assist Indego to better allocate bike share resources based on demand varying across time and space, and hopefully plan and design new bike share stations in future. The model will perform meaningfully for decision-making process. In fact, if we knew the bike station capacities, we could see when demand for bikes might drive stations to run out of bikes, and then move excess bikes from elsewhere. A program manager for a bike-share system could reasonably anticipate demand and allocate bikes ahead of time.

In summary, based on existing available bike share trip data and variables, the results from the current model shows that the model needs to be improved for predicting the demand where and when bike share trips are more frequent to take place, because current model predicts well only in the areas and time periods that the bike share is less demanded. In addition, current model should be improved to better generalize in different socio-economic contexts, so that the demand can be accurately predicted and social resources can be equally distributed among different groups of people.

This paper consists of 6 main sections which are: 1. Executive Summary 2. Data 3. Exploratory Analysis 4. Modeling 5. Results & Examination 6. Conclusion. To help you understand the process and results better, plots and their text annotation are added in the paper together with my code when necessary.

2. Data

2.1 Import 2019 Q3 Indego Bike Share Trip Data

In PhIladelphia, Quarter 3 (July 1st to September 30th) always has the best condition (temperature, intensity of sunlight, etc) for bike riding, which produces most number of bike trips among all 4 quarters. So, in order to get the most accurate analysis results, Indego bike share data from 2019 Quarter 3 is used in this project. During this time period, there are 14 weeks with 2 national holidays, Independence Day (July 4th) and Labor Day (Sept 2nd).

2.2 Import Census Data (ACS 2018 5-year)

Next, in order to explore the associations between socioeconomic factors and ride share in Philly, census data (2014-2018 American Community Survey 5-year estimates) was also collected for this project. I mainly focused on 1) percent of White population 2) mean commute time 3) percent of population who taking public transit 4) median household income and 5) median age for related analysis.

PhillyCensus <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract",

         Mean_Commute_Time = Travel_Time / Total_Public_Trans,

2.3 Import Weather Data

In addition, since weather conditions would also significantly affect peoples travel behaviors (whether riding a bike or not), the data of temperature, wind speed and precipitation on an hourly basis are considered for this project. All weather data are collected from Philadelphia International Airport (PHL).

Weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "PHL", date_start = "2019-07-01", date_end = "2019-09-30") %>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
  mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(interval60) %>%
  summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
            Precipitation = sum(p01i),
            Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
  mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

glimpse(Weather.Panel)

Temperature and precipation trends over the study period are plotted below:

grid.arrange(

3. Exploratory Analysis

3.1 Create Space-Time Panel

The dataset for the forecast must be a complete panel, meaning there must be an observation for every possible space/time combination. Since the existing data frame is an incomplete panel with missing space/time intervals, in the code block below, the panel is completed by finding all unique space/time intervals, inserting 0 trips where necessary, and then performing some additional feature engineering.

length(unique(Philly_dat_Census$interval60)) * length(unique(Philly_dat_Census$start_station))
## [1] 304014

An empty panel data frame study.panelis created that has unique space/time observations. The completestudy.panel` includes totally 304,014 space/time units, which shows that the count is correct.

study.panel <- 
  expand.grid(interval60=unique(Philly_dat_Census$interval60), 
              start_station = unique(Philly_dat_Census$start_station)) %>%
  left_join(., Philly_dat_Census %>%
              select(start_station, Origin.Tract, from_longitude, from_latitude )%>%
              distinct() %>%
              group_by(start_station) %>%
              slice(1))

nrow(study.panel)   
## [1] 304014

Then, I created the full panel by summarizing counts by station for each time interval, keep census info and lat/lon information along for joining later to other data. The data for station IDs that are FALSE are removed. The output of the code block below ensures that a balanced panel is returned - one with an equal number of observations for each space/time combination:

ride.panel <- 
  Philly_dat_Census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
  right_join(study.panel) %>% 
  group_by(interval60, start_station, Origin.Tract, from_longitude, from_latitude) %>%
  summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>%
  left_join(Weather.Panel) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is.na(start_station) == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(Origin.Tract) == FALSE)

ride.panel <- 
  left_join(ride.panel, PhillyCensus %>%
              as.data.frame() %>%
              select(-geometry), by = c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID"))

3.2 Create Time-Lag

Next, some additional feature engineering is undertaken to mine the data for critical time trends. Like spatial lags, time lags are incredibly important when predicting time series trends. To capture these trends, several different time lags are created. Two holiday fixed effects are created for Independence Day and Labor Day as well, with the hypothesis that ride share patterns will certainly change around national holidays.

ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start_station, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24),
         holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) %in% c(185, 245),1,0)) %>%
         #holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) == 185,1,0), # 7/4 Independence Day
         #holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) == 245,1,0)) %>% # 9/2 Labor Day
  mutate(day = yday(interval60)) %>%
  mutate(holidayLag = case_when(dplyr::lag(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "PlusOneDay",
                                dplyr::lag(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "PlustTwoDays",
                                dplyr::lag(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "PlustThreeDays",
                                dplyr::lead(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "MinusOneDay",
                                dplyr::lead(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "MinusTwoDays",
                                dplyr::lead(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "MinusThreeDays"),
         holidayLag = replace_na(holidayLag, 0))

# table(ride.panel$week[ride.panel$holidayLag != 0])

Furthermore, we can build an animated gif map of rideshare trips over both space and time. Week 34 & 36 which have large number of bike share trip counts are chosen to help explore the relationship. I design the time intervals as 15 minutes for Week 36 and 60 minutes for Week 34. They better show the spatial-temporal pattern of Indego bike share services than those still graphs that: 1) those trips centralized in the central part of Philadelphia, especially Center City areas 2) the time period around PM peak hours has the most number of bike share trips in a day.

4. Modeling

After conducting exploratory analysis with the variables, we had a preliminary understanding of the relationship between the use of the Indego bike share program in Philadelphia and the influence factors. In this section, the models would be built and run for predicting the distribution (time-space) patterns of the rideshare data.

4.1 Train and Test Sets Seperation

At first, the data was split into a training and a test set which are distinguished from Week 33 there are totally 7 weeks in the test set. In the next section, several regressions are run and predictions are created in a nested data frame allowing to concisely validate each model.

ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week < 33)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week >= 33)

4.2 Model Building and Estimation

In this step, 5 linear models are created using the lm function in the training set, but made predictions and get results in the test set. The reason why I dont use an algorithm like Poisson over OLS even though the dependent variable (Trip Count) in the model is a count and not continuous is: The counts are sufficiently large to feel at ease with OLS.

Here is a breakdown of the 5 regressions estimated below:

Model 1: reg1, focuses on just time effects. The first model includes hour fixed effects, day of the week fixed effects and temperature. Lag effects are not included for now.

Model 2: reg2, replaces the time fixed effects with a vector of origin tracts fixed effects.

Model 3: reg3, includes both time and space fixed effects.

Model 4: reg4, adds the time lag features.

Model 5: reg5, adds holiday and holidayLag effects.

reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg4 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station +  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
       lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day, data=ride.Train)

reg5 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
       lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday, data=ride.Train)

4.3 Test Data Prediction

Then, I created a nested data frame of test data by week. A function called model_pred which can be used to map onto each data frame in the nested structure was created as well. What makes the nested format so powerful, is the ability to loop through each week and mutate summary statistics for each model. In the code block below, week_predictions are calculated for each week in ride.Test. This accomplished by way of the map function, which is designed to apply a function to each element.

ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(-week) 

model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
  pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}

week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
  mutate(ATime_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
         BSpace_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
         CTime_Space_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred),
         DTime_Space_FE_timeLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg4, .f = model_pred),
         ETime_Space_FE_timeLags_holidayLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg5, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
  gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
  mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
         Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
         MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
         sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))

week_predictions

5. Results & Examination

After running the predictions, the results from all 5 models were got in the end of the previous section. In this section, the results would be examined in the aspects of accuracy and generalizability.

5.1 Examine Error Metrics for Accuracy

The best models - the lag models (in general, they have the smallest MAE among all models), are accurate to less than an average of one ride per hour, at a glance, thats pretty alright for overall accuracy.

The MAE is plotted by model specifification for each week below. We see that the holiday effects do not bring much additional predictive power to the model, except for Week 35 & 36. In the other weeks, holiday effects make the prediction less accurate. Note that both the training and test has one holiday. However, the fact shows that holiday effects do not work well.

# MAE by model specification and week
week_predictions %>%
  dplyr::select(week, Regression, MAE) %>%
  gather(Variable, MAE, -Regression, -week) %>%
  ggplot(aes(week, MAE)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Regression), position = "dodge", stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette5) +
  labs(title = "Mean Absolute Errors by model specification and week",
       subtitle = "Bike share trip predicton; A test set of 7 weeks; Philadelphia, July through Sept 2019") +
  plotTheme

In addition, for each model, the predicted and observed trip count is plotted in time series form below. Probably the simple, most all-encompassing interpretation of the results below is that with increasing sophistication, it becomes increasingly possible to predict well for the trip count spikes.

According to the plots, the spatial fixed effects alone dont help predict the time trend. Models A and C that include time and time/space fixed effects respectively, appear to be have the same time trends because in this plot, all the predictions are aggregated from their spatial context to time alone.

It is also clear to see time lag effects add a tremendous amount of predictive power to this model, very nearly predicting the highest spikes. Not surprisingly, bike share patterns from the very recent past do a great job predicting in the near future. But simply based on the plot, holiday effects dont bring consipicuous predictive power either.

# Predicted/Observed bike share time series
week_predictions %>% 
  mutate(interval60 = map(data, pull, interval60),
         start_station = map(data, pull, start_station)) %>%
  dplyr::select(interval60, start_station, Observed, Prediction, Regression) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -Regression, -interval60, -start_station) %>%
  group_by(Regression, Variable, interval60) %>%
  summarize(Value = sum(Value)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(interval60, Value, colour=Variable)) + 
   scale_colour_manual("",values = c("Observed" = "darkgray","Prediction" = "#006699")) +
  geom_line(size = 1) + 
  facet_wrap(~Regression, ncol=1) +
  labs(title = "Predicted/Observed bike share trips by time series", 
       subtitle = "Philadelphia, July through Sept 2019; A test set of 7 weeks",  
       x = "Hour", y= "Station Trips") +
  plotTheme

Therefore, through examining Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and the plot above, I believe the fourth model which has time lages but no holiday effects seems to have the best goodness of fit generally.

5.2 Generalizability

There are different dimensions to test the generalizability of the model (Model 4): time, space and socio-economic factors. The core question to be answered is: does the model predict well in different context of those dimensions?

5.2.1 Validate test set by time

If we plot observed vs.predicted for different times of day during the week and weekend, as shown in the plots below, some patterns begin to emerge. However, we are certainly underpredicting in general.

5.2.3 Validate test set by Socio-economic Factors

Finally, the model is examined under socio-economic Factors. As shown in the plot of errors below, the model doesnt predict well equally for different socio-economic contexts.

Mean commute time: the model predicts pretty well where people spend less commute time.

Percent of population taking public transit: the model predicts pretty well where there is higher percent of population taking public transit.

Median age: the model predicts pretty well where people with median age around 20 and median age above 50.

Percent of White population: the model predicts well where there is fewer percent of White population.

Median household income: the model predicts well where there is lower median household income (less than 30,000).

#Error as a function of socio-economic factors

  unnest() %>%
  filter(Regression == "ETime_Space_FE_timeLags_holidayLags")%>%
  mutate(weekend = ifelse(dotw %in% c("Sun", "Sat"), "Weekend", "Weekday"),
         time_of_day = case_when(hour(interval60) < 7 | hour(interval60) > 18 ~ "Overnight",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 10 & hour(interval60) < 15 ~ "Mid-Day",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 15 & hour(interval60) <= 18 ~ "PM Rush")) %>%
  filter(time_of_day == "AM Rush") %>%
  group_by(start_station, Percent_Taking_Public_Trans, Med_Inc, Percent_White, Med_Age,Mean_Commute_Time) %>%

  gather(-start_station, -MAE, key = "variable", value = "value")%>%

6. Conclusion

In conclusion, the model does not predict well for where and when more trips are likely to occur, as there are higher errors taking place in those context, for example, the rush hours in Central City, which may result in lack of bycicles in high demand areas and time periods. Moreover, the key takeaway is that the model underpredicts the bike share demand during rush hours in Central City in weekdays. Therefore, one piece of advice is, Indego should supply more bike share during those time slots in Central City, and people should be prepared to schedule well if they need to use bike share service at those times in Central City.

Furthermore, the existences of errors in the spatial pattern indicates that the model still has some issues with spatial autocorrelation. Perhaps I can add spatial lags in the model to better illustrate the spatial structure of the data. In addition, when I set errors as a function of socio-economic variables, it shows that the model doesnt predict well in certain groups, which may be improved by adding new features like the gender of the users, the travel time of the trips, and so on

Finally, the positive side of the model is that its good at predicting when and where trips are less frequent, such as non-rush hour during weekdays and in the areas aways from Central City, which could be refered by Indego when they would like to improve their services.
